    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-01-30T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-01-30T07:00:00-05:00" n="90"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d90">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/4473</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-01-30T13:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 30, 1917, 1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received January 31, 6.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4951. My 4925. Your 3834. I have now been given by friend in high office here a
                    copy of the German memorandum about armed merchant vessels which I am told
                        <persName corresp="#p_BJHC1">Bernstorff</persName> has delivered to you. My
                    copy is undated, is in German, and is headed “Memorandum of the German
                    Government concerning the defensively armed enemy merchant vessels.” It cites
                    evidence and certain specific cases tending to prove that French and British
                    merchant vessels are armed for offensive purposes and states that the German
                    Government has come to the conclusion that such ships must be treated as ships
                    of war. In this connection it refers to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LR1"
                        >Lansing</persName>’s note of January 18, 1916, to the British
                        Ambassador<note n="1" xml:id="d90fn1">
                        <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_146">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, Supplement, p.
                        146</ref>.</note> in which it is clearly stated that <pb facs="0269" n="97"
                        xml:id="pg_97"/> at the present time all arming of merchant vessels would
                    appear to have the character of offensive armament since the mounting of guns on
                    merchant vessels can only be declared to have the intention of enabling the
                    merchant vessels to prevent warning and search on the part of submarine boats.
                    If you desire full copy we shall translate and cable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
